            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#b">SAVAGE PREJUDICES.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The natives near the cataracts or <choice><sic>randales</sic><corr
                            type="editorial">raudales</corr></choice> of the<lb break="yes"
                    />Oroonoko, up which M. de Humboldt made his way<lb break="yes"/>to a height
                    little known to Europeans, are distinguished<lb break="yes"/>by several
                    remarkable prejudices, among which, none<lb break="yes"/>are more fatal than
                    those narrated in the following:&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;Among the
                    causes of the depopulation of the <choice><sic>Ran-<lb break="no"
                            />dales</sic><corr type="editorial">Rau-<lb break="no"
                        />dales</corr></choice>, I have not reckoned the small pox; that malady<lb
                        break="yes"/>which, in other parts of America, makes such cruel<lb
                        break="yes"/>ravages, that the natives, seized with dismay, burn<lb
                        break="yes"/>their huts, kill their children, and renounce every<lb
                        break="yes"/>kind of society. This scourge is almost unknown on<lb
                        break="yes"/>the banks of the Oroonoko. What depopulates the<lb break="yes"
                    />Christian settlement is, the repugnance of the Indians<lb break="yes"/>for the
                    regulations of the missions, the insalubrity of a<lb break="yes"/>climate at
                    once hot and damp, bad nourishment, want<lb break="yes"/>of care in the diseases
                    of children, and the guilty prac-<lb break="no"/>tice of mothers of preventing
                    pregnancy by the use of<lb break="yes"/>deleterious herbs. Among the barbarous
                    people of<lb break="yes"/>Guyana, as well as those of the half-civilized
                        islands<lb break="yes"/>of the South Sea, young wives will not become mo-<lb
                        break="no"/>thers. If they have children, their offspring are exposed,<lb
                        break="yes"/>not only to the dangers of savage life, but also to the<lb
                        break="yes"/>dangers arising from the strangest popular prejudices.<lb
                        break="yes"/>When twins are born, false notions of propriety and<lb
                        break="yes"/>family honour require, that one of them should be<lb
                        break="yes"/>destroyed. &#x2018;To bring twins into the world, is to be<lb
                        break="yes"/>exposed to public scorn: it is to resemble rats, opos-<lb
                        break="no"/>sums, and the vilest animals, which bring forth a great<lb
                        break="yes"/>number of young at a time.&#x2019; Nay more: &#x2018;two
                        chil-<lb break="no"/>dren born at the same time cannot belong to the same<lb
                        break="yes"/>family.&#x2019; This is an axiom of physiology of the Sali-<lb
                        break="no"/>vas; and in every zone, and in different states of society,<lb
                        break="yes"/>when the vulgar seize upon an axiom, they adhere to<lb
                        break="yes"/>it with more stedfastness than the better informed men,<lb
                        break="yes"/>by whom it was first hazarded. To avoid a disturb-<lb
                        break="no"/>ance of conjugal tranquillity, the old female relations<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the mother, or the <hi rendition="#i">mure-japoicnei</hi>
                    (midwives) take<lb break="yes"/>care that one of the twins shall disappear. If
                    the new<lb break="yes"/>born infant, though not a twin, have any physical de-<lb
                        break="no"/>formity, the father instantly puts it to death. They<lb
                        break="yes"/>will have only robust and well-made children, for defor-<lb
                        break="no"/>mities indicate some influence of the evil spirit Ioloqui-<lb
                        break="no"/>amo, or the bird <hi rendition="#i">Tikitiki,</hi> the enemy of
                    the human race.<lb break="yes"/>Sometimes children of a feeble constitution
                    undergo the<lb break="yes"/>same fate. When the father is asked what is
                        become<lb break="yes"/>of one of his sons, he will pretend that he has lost
                        him<lb break="yes"/>by a natural death; he will disavow an action that
                        ap-<lb break="no"/>pears to him blameable, but not criminal. &#x2018;The
                        poor<lb break="yes"/><hi rendition="#i">mure</hi>&#x201D; (child) he will
                    tell you, &#x2018;could not follow us;<lb break="yes"/><cb/>we must have waited
                    for him every moment; he has<lb break="yes"/>not been seen again; he did not
                    come to sleep where we<lb break="yes"/>passed the night.&#x2019; Such is the
                    candour and simplicity of<lb break="yes"/>manners, such the boasted happiness of
                    man in a <hi rendition="#i">state<lb break="yes"/>of nature!</hi> He kills his
                    son to escape the ridicule of<lb break="yes"/>having twins, or to avoid
                    journeying more slowly; in<lb break="yes"/>fact, to avoid a little
                    inconvenience.</p>
